				<p><p>Since you mention that you are using a <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CRS_Robotics" rel="nofollow">CRS Catalyst 5</a> arm, I assume that you are using the <a href="http://www.thermoscientific.fr/com/cda/product/detail/0,1055,21981,00.html" rel="nofollow">CRS ActiveRobot</a> ActiveX control.</p>

<p>A quick look through <a href="http://www.scribd.com/doc/44659351/Tutorial-Active-Robot" rel="nofollow">this ActiveRobot Tutorial</a> suggests that <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Asynchronous_method_invocation" rel="nofollow">all robot commands are asynchronous</a>, so when you command the gripper to open (using <code>Robot.GripperOpen</code> in VB) you then have to wait for the move to finish (using <code>Robot.GripperFinish</code> in VB).</p>

<p>Similarly it looks like you need to wait for a <code>Robot.MoveStraight</code> to complete with a <code>Robot.Finish</code> etc.</p>

<p>Replace all of your sleep calls with the relevant wait commands and you will get rid of all of the unwanted <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dead_time" rel="nofollow">dead time</a>. Similarly if you wait for one move to finish before starting a subsequent move, you may prevent moves conflicting with eact other, confusing the control system.</p>
</p><br>
